The system under consideration models a digital camera application designed using a component-based, message-passing architecture suitable for embedded implementation. The specification abstracts the overall behavior of a digital imaging device, capturing the main functional blocks typically found in a modern camera system. The design begins with a stimulus component, representing an image source, such as a sensor or a test pattern generator. This component initiates the dataflow, pushing structured image data into the system. The core of the system, encapsulated within a component named DigitalCam, manages image acquisition, control signaling, and compression. Following processing, the resulting data is delivered to a display unit that acts as a rendering endpoint. Communication among components is explicitly defined through ports and channels, supporting both synchronous and asynchronous interactions. The entire application is modeled at a high level of abstraction, promoting design portability and enabling early validation through simulation or formal analysis tools commonly used in electronic design automation workflows.